entry.title: [Files]: A different approach to slow recent sources.
entry.content:
The original approach used a sequence ID to distinguish between desired

and late callback calls. However, each source would store callback and

other parameters locally. This meant that it was possible for a slow

source to be busy for so long that if a new request came and the local

variables were overwritten, the old call would come back just in time to

use the newly set instance variable specific to the new call.



Thus we adopt a new approach. Each source can be explicitly stopped.

Each source holds a map from call ID to the context needed by that call.

If the Stop call comes, it deletes the context associated with the

given call ID. This way when a new call is made, the new context is

only accessible with the new call ID, which is unknown to the old

invocation.

entry.title: language_pack_font_service: Use real service initialisation in tests
entry.content:
Before this CL, all profile `KeyedServices` were being constructed when

the `TestingProfile` was created. However, `LanguagePackFontService` was

not being constructed because the feature was disabled by default. This

caused test failures when the feature was enabled by default, as _two_

`LanguagePackFontService`s were being created in tests - one in the

profile, in in the test.



To fix this, we enable the feature by default - to explicitly create the

service with the profile - and override the factory so a real

`LanguagePackFontService` instance is created, except with a mock

`AddFontDir` implementation.



As the tests modified preferences _before_ the `LanguagePackFontService`

was available (to test logic in the initialisation of the service), this

CL also explicitly creates a `TestingPrefServiceSyncable` to use before

the profile is available and initialised.

entry.title: Revert "Ignore drag events while waiting to exit a nested run loop."
entry.content:
This reverts commit d933cbd269533f69b334f8a3d7c32c00b8211240.



Reason for revert: The new test fails consistently on Linux Tests (Wayland):



https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20Tests%20(Wayland)/51887/overview



Original change's description:

> Ignore drag events while waiting to exit a nested run loop.

>

> Background: When dragging tabs into another window, TabDragController exits the nested run loop that was handling the window drag and resumes handling the drag session within the original, parent run loop. But that is not an atomic event - it must return control and wait for the nested run loop to exit. If any additional calls into TabDragController::Drag happen between TabDragController asking to exit the run loop and that nested run loop actually exiting, TabDragController could do unexpected things while handling those events. Notably, if it tried to start another nested run loop, this would CHECK.

>

> This CL extends TabDragController's DragState state enum to explicitly model this interval with a `kWaitingToExitRunLoop` state, so it can ignore calls to Drag during this interval.

>

> It's worth noting that some platforms (Chrome OS and Linux) will use this new state, and others (Windows and Mac) will not because they instead already use the kWaitingToDragTabs state during the same interval. These are modeled separately because they correspond to very different underlying states for the drag session - see the comments on the enum values for details.

entry.title: Fix the Mac blink_unittests build
entry.content:
When not using reclient, on some Mac OS versions, the

comiler insists that classes be fully defined in order

to compare Mamber<> objects. The StyleSheetContents used

in style_scope.h was not fuly defined yet was being checked

for nullptr, and this was causing build errors.



Fix it by comparing contents_.Get() to nullptr, which avoids

the problematic template expansion.

entry.title: Disable multi-process app-bound encryption tests for component builds
entry.content:
As part of testing app-bound encryption, the tests use

temporary executables with various names, path locations, and

attributes (such as digital signature) to verify different

behaviors in the identity capture part of the elevation service.



However, in component builds, the test executable has many DLL

dependencies as part of the build, meaning it cannot easily be

hermetically moved to different locations on disk to truly

test these behaviors.



Because of this, this CL disables the multi-process app-bound

encryption tests on component builds.



Since component builds are not shipped, this does not affect

test coverage for production builds, which are still fully

covered by all the tests.



BUG=324456506

entry.title: media/gpu: Add H.264 Frame Num passthrough when not supported
entry.content:
The ToT H.264 decoder was setup to detect and handle frame number

gaps. If a frame gap is detected, the decoder will check if the

sequence allows gaps via the |gaps_in_frame_num_value_allowed_flag|. If

this flag is set to false, the decoder will log that it is invalid, but

will try to handle the frame num gap anyway which causes issues on some

platforms.



Updates the H.264 decoder logic to add passthrough logic to the

HandleFrameNumGap function if the |gaps_in_frame_num_value_allowed_flag|

is set to false. If set to false, it will log that it is ignoring the

frame num gap and returning true, acting as a passthrough.



Bug: b:311839666

video.ChromeStackDecoderVerification.h264_files_from_bugs_299320432 on
